---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { SITE, FRESH_DAYS } from '../consts';
import { breadcrumbLd } from '../lib/seo';

const title = 'About & data sources';
const description = `How ${SITE.name} gets its lake-level data, how percent-full is computed, the freshness policy, and the data-source list (USGS, CDEC).`;
const ld = [breadcrumbLd([{ name: 'Home', path: '/' }, { name: 'About', path: '/about' }])];
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} path="/about" jsonLd={ld}>
  <div class="container">
    <article class="prose">
      <h1>About {SITE.name}</h1>
      <p>{SITE.name} shows the current water level and percent full for US lakes and reservoirs, pulled straight from
      public water-data feeds — not scraped from other websites. The goal is a single, fast, honest place to see how full
      a lake is right now, how it's trending, and whether you can realistically launch a boat.</p>

      <h2 id="data-sources">Where the data comes from</h2>
      <p>Each lake's reading comes from its own authoritative feed:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>USGS Water Services</b> — thousands of US gages (gage height and reservoir elevation). Free, keyless, updates as often as every 15–60 minutes.</li>
        <li><b>CDEC (California Data Exchange)</b> — California reservoir storage and elevation, daily. Used for Shasta, Oroville, Folsom, Berryessa, and the other CA reservoirs.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mut">Additional feeds (LCRA HydroMet for the Texas Highland Lakes, USBR for Mead/Powell, USACE district data) are wired in as the registry grows.</p>

      <h2 id="methodology">How we compute things</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Percent full</b> = current storage (acre-feet) &divide; the reservoir's published full capacity, as a percentage. Where only elevation is available, we show elevation in feet above mean sea level and feet below full pool instead.</li>
        <li><b>Feet below full pool</b> = full-pool elevation &minus; current elevation. Positive means the lake is below full; negative means above (during flood pools).</li>
        <li><b>24-hour change</b> = difference between the two most recent readings in the series.</li>
        <li><b>~30-day trend</b> = the sparkline of the last ~30 daily/instantaneous readings.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="freshness">Freshness policy (why a reading may say "delayed")</h2>
      <p>A reading is shown as live only if it is within {FRESH_DAYS} days. If a gage hasn't reported recently, {SITE.name}
      flags it "may be delayed" rather than pass an old number off as current. Lakes whose feed isn't yet wired show
      reference data and a note — never a fabricated level.</p>

      <h2 id="accuracy">Accuracy &amp; your responsibility</h2>
      <p>These are point-in-time readings from public feeds; they can lag real conditions, and reservoir operators can
      change releases and gate operations at any time. Percent-full is a guide computed from published capacities.
      Always confirm current ramp status, hazards, and conditions with the lake operator
      (USACE, USBR, the state agency, or local authority) before you go on the water. {SITE.name} is not affiliated with
      any government agency.</p>

      <h2 id="contact">Contact</h2>
      <p>Spot a wrong gage, a mislabeled lake, or a feed you'd like added? Email <a href={`mailto:${SITE.contactEmail}`}>{SITE.contactEmail}</a>.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
